{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17507928","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17507928"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:59:29+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:59:29+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2691"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2691","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2691"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.53,0.15,0.13,0.04,0.15]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2691"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76271"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2691","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2691"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2691"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61775"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3269"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3359"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9811"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9824"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76271","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76271"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 26-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic for pre-travel advice. He plans to travel overseas for two months. He has a medical history of Hodgkin lymphoma and completed chemotherapy one month ago. He takes no regular medications. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following vaccinations is the most appropriate to administer prior to travel?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Influenza","Yellow fever","Measles-mumps-rubella","Varicella","Japanese encephalitis live vaccine"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient requires pre-travel vaccination advice but is immunocompromised due to both his underlying Hodgkin lymphoma and recent chemotherapy. The key principle is that live vaccines are contraindicated in immunocompromised patients due to the risk of vaccine-strain infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInfluenza\u003C/strong\u003E vaccine is an inactivated vaccine that is safe and recommended annually for immunocompromised patients. It is particularly important for those planning to travel as influenza circulates year-round in tropical areas and during winter in temperate regions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EYellow fever\u003C/strong\u003E vaccine contains live attenuated virus and is absolutely contraindicated in immunocompromised patients. If travel to yellow fever endemic areas cannot be avoided, these patients should receive a medical exemption certificate and be counselled about mozzie avoidance measures.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMeasles-mumps-rubella\u003C/strong\u003E vaccine is a live vaccine that is contraindicated during immunosuppression. While measles poses particular risks to immunocompromised patients, the live vaccine cannot safely be given until immune function has recovered.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVaricella\u003C/strong\u003E vaccine is also a live vaccine contraindicated in immunocompromised patients. The inactivated recombinant zoster vaccine (Shingrix) can be given instead if protection against varicella-zoster virus is needed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EJapanese encephalitis live vaccine\u003C/strong\u003E (Imojev) is contraindicated, though the inactivated version (JEspect) can be safely administered if indicated by travel plans.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther inactivated vaccines that may be appropriate depending on destination include hepatitis A, hepatitis B, meningococcal, and injectable typhoid vaccines. The patient should also receive advice about food and water precautions, insect protection, and the importance of travel insurance that covers medical evacuation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Live vaccinations are contraindicated in immunocompromised patients due to risk of vaccine-strain infection","Inactivated vaccines including influenza are safe and recommended for immunocompromised patients","Pre-travel vaccination advice must consider both destination risks and patient immune status"],"references":["Australian Technical Advisory Group on Immunisation (ATAGI). Vaccination for people who are immunocompromised [Internet]. Australian Immunisation Handbook: Department of Health, Australian Government; 2019 [updated 2020 June 3; cited 2021 July 26]. Available from: https://immunisationhandbook.health.gov.au/vaccination-for-special-risk-groups/vaccination-for-people-who-are-immunocompromised","Asking HH, Rombo L, Andersson Y, Martin S, Ekdahl K. Hepatitis A Risk in Travelers. J Travel Med 2009. [cited 2021 Jul 26]; 16:233-238.","Australian Technical Advisory Group on Immunisation (ATAGI). Vaccination for international travellers [Internet]. Australian Immunisation Handbook: Department of Health, Australian Government; 2023 [updated 2023 May 11; cited 2023 Sept 10]. Available from: https://immunisationhandbook.health.gov.au/vaccination-for-special-risk-groups/vaccination-for-international-travellers"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61775"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2691"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61775","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61775"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"20